Computer Assisted Tools for Septuagint/Scriptural Studies (CATSS) Project Textual Variants Module
 
Second Maccabees Variants file 
 

Prepared by Gil Renberg,  October  2000 

 
This is the penultimate draft of the text and variants. Many queries and calls for verification or correction remain in the file (in bold type), but rather than hold this material back from circulation until there is time to edit it more fully, we hereby make it available with this warning about its unfinished character. 
 
Robert Kraft, director of the CATSS variants sub-project at the 
  University of Pennsylvania (02 June 2004).

 

 

NOTE:  I do not know Syriac, so search for every instance of <sy> and make sure it is correct. – Gil

NOTE:  Beginning at 5:1, I have used [=] to signal all instances of the app.crit. putting a Latin variant immediately after a Greek one, without separating them with a semi-colon.  There are a few dozen instances of this before chapt. 5, so someone would need to go back and look for them. - Gil

PRE-NOTES NOTE: These notes by my predecessors are no longer relevant, and can be ignored.  - Gil

 

   NOTES: I got to the end of chapter 10 before I stopped. 

There are some places along the way where I did not

insert the variant (because they were in Latin, too

complicated/ambiguous for me, or both).  Those places

are boxed on the hard copy.  Let me know if I can help

sort anything out.               (Pax,)  Max.

   NOTES 2 (Allen K.): I did 11:1 through 14:5.  Where a

superscripted minus sign is used in the apparatus, I

have typed the minus sign inside the superscript markers

rather than outside them; e.g., I type <lt>L</>’{-19}

instead of <lt>L</>’-{19}. The placement inside

corresponds much more closely to the visual impact of

the hard copy than does the placement outside and, more

important, it corresponds more closely conceptually.  It

also distinguishes this use of the keyboarded hyphen

from the keyboarded hyphen used to signify a group such

as 46-52, where the hyphen is not superscripted.  Dr.

Bob agrees that the inside placement is preferable over

the outside placement which is written in the original

guide.  Previous work using the older outside placement

is thus inconsistent with this newer style and will have

to be corrected in the end.  I apologize for the

inevitable mistakes and errors of method that escaped

me.
